The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Indians sole leaders

Isfahan (Iran): Indian men started off with a 3.5-0.5 victory over Afghanistan and emerged sole leaders after the first round of the Asian Team Chess Championship that got underway here. 

With a depleted field in absence of defending champions China, the Asian Team Championship has six teams competing this year including two from the host country. 

The other participants are Turkmenistan and Vietnam, apart from India and Afghanistan. 

The Indians are led by Grandmaster Krishnan Sasikiran on the top board. 

IM Sundar Rajan Kidambi dropped half a point on the third board against Farazi Khaiber, but the GMs Surya Shekhar Ganguly, Abhijit Kunte and Sandipan Chanda coasted to easy wins to help India emerge as sole leader with 3.5 points. 

On other boards, Turkmenistan and Iran B took a point each from second seed Vietnam and third seed Iran A, respectively. 

Sasikiran was rested in the first round game and Kunte took board one for India to crush Asefi Zaheeruddeen of Afghanistan. 

It was a similar story for National champion Surya Sekhar and Chanda, who both outclassed Fidaeyee Habibullah and Sarway Hamidullah, respectively. 

In womens category, Indian eves took off on a cautious note, sharing points with Vietnam. 

On the top board, WGM Nisha Mohota was beaten by Nguyen Thi Thanh but Bengals Mary Ann Gomes levelled the scores after accounting for Luong Minh Hue. 

On the third board, Swathi Ghate drew with Hoang Thi Bao Tram. 

 (PTI) 




